lidden, Miriam Libicki, and Liana Finck. Rooted in a conception of identity based as much on rebellion as identification and belonging, these artists' representations of Jewishness take shape in the spaces between how we see ourselves and how others see us. They experiment with different representations and affiliations without forgetting that identity ties the self to others. Stemming from Kominsky Crumb's iconic 1989 comic "Nose Job," in which her alter ego refuses to assimilate through cosmetic surgery, Oksman's study is an arresting exploration of invention in the face of the pressure to disappear.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiography in literature. 0aComic books, strips, etcxHistory and criticism. 0aComic books, strips, etc.xHistory and criticism. 0aGraphic novelsxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish women in literature. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aWomen in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/oksm1727440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231540780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231540780.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles